vscode-mssql Private Preview #1 Getting Started Guide

vscode-mssql is the Microsoft SQL Tools extension for working with SQL Server from Visual Studio Code. It provides the ability to connect to SQL Server, Azure DB, and SQL Server on Linux instances. This guide introduces the vscode-mssql feature areas.

Activating the Extension

vscode-mssql is loaded when a SQL file is opened in VS Code. This can be done by opening a file with a .sql file extension or by opening a new text editor and changing the file to SQL. To change an editor's file text to SQL locate the file type indicator in the status bar. It will say "Plain Text" by default.

Clicking on the file type indicator will display the Language Mode selection list in the Command Palette. Select the "SQL" option.

Connection Management

Most interaction with the VS Code is done through the Command Palette. The Command Palette can be activated with the Ctrl-Shift-P or Cmd-Shift-P keyboard shortcut. vscode-mssql commands all begin with the 'MSSQL'' prefix.

Connection management is based on the concept of Connection Profiles, which is saved metadata about a user's SQL Servers and databases. To connect to a database create a Connection Profile with the "MSSQL: Create Connection Profile"" command. This command will prompt the user for values necessary to establish a database connection.

Once a connection profile is create it can be subsequently accessed through the "MSSQL: Connect to a database" command.

When the active editor is connected to a database the connection details with be displayed in the status bar.

T-SQL Editor

The T-SQL editor supports T-SQL colorization, syntax & schema error diagnostics, autocomplete, and snippets. Error diagnostics show up as red squiggles in the editor and as error messages in the error list tool window.

Schema autocomplete only is supported after a connection has been established. The suggests are context-aware based on the current database schema and the SQL text. Ctrl-Space triggers the autocomplete pop-up at any time.

Snippets are accessible through the autocomplete menu. Snippet expansions support tab-complete to provide template parameter values.

Query Execution

Queries can be executed after a connection has been established. The "MSSQL: Run T-SQL Query"" command will execute the current SQL file or select SQL text (shortcut CTRL-SHIFT-E).

While a query is running the status bar is updated to show the execution progress.

If there are multiple SQL queries in a file then multiple resultsets will be displayed in stackable grid controls in the result preview window.

The results can be exported as either CSV or JSON using the context menu on the grid control.

Known Issues

OpenSSL needs to be installed on Mac

Missing package on Ubuntu 14
